         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1539">
               <p>A Welshman awakened under the preaching of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName> in
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> around <date when="1750">1750</date>, Olivers
                  moved some months later to <placeName>Bradford-on-Avon</placeName> where he became
                  a member of the Methodist society and an exhorter. In <date when="1753"
                     >1753</date> he accepted a call from <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> to become a <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">traveling preacher</seg>, and served faithfully throughout
                     <placeName>Great Britain</placeName> and <placeName>Ireland</placeName> until
                     <date when="1776">1776</date>, when <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> asked him to superintend the
                  printing operation in <placeName>London</placeName>. At this he was only
                  moderately successful, so that <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> eventually replaced him. Nevertheless, he was a prodigious
                  worker and a prolific writer in defense of Methodism. His most lasting memorial is
                  probably his hymn, &apos;The God of Abraham praise&apos;. See Atmore, <hi
                     rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 302–6; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 843; <hi
                     rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 2:48–106; <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley,
                     <date when="1799">1799</date>), 2:4; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 259–60.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
